</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#DEDFDF">
<TD valign=top>
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Drew Davis
</FONT></TD>
<TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Harmony does not eliminate aggro or adjust faction in any way.  Harmony _does_ reduce the aggro radius of a mob to something very small -- perhaps not zero, but small.  If you get close enough to a Harmonized mob, it will still aggro on you, because it still hates you.  But because the aggro radius is small, you can get much closer than normal.<P>   You generally use Harmony to break camps.  Harmony everything around, but for the one you want to pull, as others have said.  Then, since everyone else's aggro radius is small, you're more likely to be able to pull just that one out without any "linked" ones coming along.  (Linked mobs are linked because of overlapping aggro radii, not any special code telling them to join together.)  If you pull such that your target runs over a Harmonized mob, you'll still get the add, as the pulled one will get inside the aggro radius of the "safe" one and aggro it as well, just as always happens if you pull a mad mob too close to one of its friends.<P>   Harmony does not aggro the targets if it is resisted, and if you don't get a resist message, it always works.  (That's handy if you're far enough away to not get the icon on yourself, or see the lightshow.)  If you're close enough to see the name of a mob over its head, then you'll be able to see the spell effects on the mob, and know whether or not it was within the Harmony area.  It's safest to just Harmony everything if you're not sure, as was noted.  It's occasionally useful to get close that you you, yourself, are within the area.  You'll Harmony yourself, and get an icon, which is handy for letting you know when the spell wears off all the other mobs, mostly for pulling several in a row without having to re-Harmony.<P>   Harmony only works outdoors.</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR bgcolor="#F7F7F7">
<TD valign=top>
